{{improverefs|date=November 2013}} {{PoliticsRofI}} {{distinguish|Council of State (Ireland)}} The '''Presidential Commission''' ({{Lang-ga|Coimisi√∫n na hUachtar√°nachta}}) is the collective vice-presidency of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].
==Membership== Three members serve on the Presidential Commission.
{| class=wikitable |- !Office !Description !Incumbent |- | [[Chief Justice of Ireland|Chief Justice]] | President of the [[Supreme Court of Ireland|Supreme Court]] | [[Frank Clarke (judge)|Frank Clarke]] |- | [[Ceann Comhairle]] | Chairman of [[D√°il √âireann]] | [[Se√°n √ì Feargha√≠l]] |- | [[Cathaoirleach]] | Chairman of [[Seanad √âireann]] | [[Denis O Donovan]] |}
The President of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] acts as a member in place of the Chief Justice if that office is vacant. The [[Leas-Cheann Comhairle]] acts as a member in place of the Ceann Comhairle if that office is vacant. The [[Leas-Chathaoirleach]] acts as a member in place of the Cathaoirleach if that office is vacant.<ref>Constitution of Ireland, Articles 14.2.2, 14.2.3, 14.2.4.</ref> The Commission may act with at least two members.<ref>Constitution of Ireland, Article 14.3.</ref>
A proposal to abolish the Seanad, which was [[Thirty-second Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2013|rejected at referendum in 2013]], would have seen the Leas-Cheann Comhairle take the place of the Cathaoirleach on the Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/viewdoc.asp?fn=/documents/bills28/bills/2013/6313/b63a13d.pdf#page=36|title=Thirty-second Amendment of the Constitution (Abolition of Seanad √âireann) Bill 2013 As passed by both Houses of the Oireachtas|date=17 July 2013|work=Bills 1997-2013|publisher=Oireachtas|page=36 Schedule 3, Part 2, No.9|accessdate=9 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/referendum-2013/seanad-results|title=Seanad Results|work=[[The Irish Times]]|date=5 October 2013}}</ref>
==Powers== The Presidential Commission fulfills all functions and duties of the office of [[President of Ireland]] when the office of President is vacant, or when the President is unavailable.
Vacancy may occur: * on the death of the incumbent, as in 1974; * on the resignation of the incumbent, as in 1976 and 1997; * by [[impeachment#Republic_of_Ireland|impeachment]] of the incumbent, which has never happened. * in the short interval between the conclusion of one president's term of office and the inauguration of a successor the next day ‚Äî although the Presidential Commission has never been required to act in this time;
The Presidential Commission has often acted when the President is abroad, typically while making a [[state visit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citizensinformation.ie/en/government_in_ireland/the_president/presidential_commission.html|title=Presidential Commission|date=1 May 2008|work=Citizens Information|publisher=Citizens Information Board|accessdate=21 December 2010|location=Dublin}}</ref> When the [[government of the 26th D√°il]] collapsed in November 1992, president [[Mary Robinson]] was abroad. The resignation of the [[Progressive Democrats]] ministers, the appointment by Taoiseach [[Albert Reynolds]] of caretaker [[Fianna F√°il]] replacement ministers, and Reynolds' request for a [[dissolution of parliament|dissolution of the D√°il]], were all effected by the Presidential Commission.<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/1992/11/05/00004.asp Private Business. - Ministerial Changes: Statement] D√°il debates, 5 November 1992</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10615F9345E0C758CDDA80994DA494D81|title=Leader Defeated, Irish Government Collapses|last=Clarity|first=James F.|date=6 November 1992|work=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> Temporary illness may also indispose the President. No President has ever refused to fulfil any of the duties of office.
==Origins== {{Wikisource|Constitution of Ireland}} The Presidential Commission was created in the 1937 [[Constitution of Ireland]]. It was first used between December 1937, when the Constitution came into force, and June 1938, when the first President was inaugurated. Initially, as the Irish senate had not been constituted and elected, the seat on the Presidential Commission intended for the Cathaoirleach of Seanad √âireann was filled by the President of the High Court under the Transitory Provisions of the Constitution.
